WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:06.190
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:06.190 --> 00:00:08.130
&gt;&gt; Saundra Smith McBee:
It is my honor today

00:00:08.130 --> 00:00:11.820
to introduce Mr. Paul Rudnick.

00:00:11.820 --> 00:00:15.700
Mr. Rudnick is an American
playwright, novelist,

00:00:15.700 --> 00:00:18.450
screenwriter and essayist.

00:00:18.450 --> 00:00:21.500 position:56%
His plays have been produced both on

00:00:21.500 --> 00:00:26.020
and off Broadway and
around the world.

00:00:26.020 --> 00:00:29.230
Rudnick was born and
raised in Piscataway,

00:00:29.230 --> 00:00:33.510
New Jersey where his
mother Selma was a publicist

00:00:33.510 --> 00:00:37.350
and his father Norman
was a physicist.

00:00:37.350 --> 00:00:42.440
Rudnick attended Yale College
before moving to New York City

00:00:42.440 --> 00:00:47.080
where he wrote his book jacket
copy and worked as an assistant

00:00:47.080 --> 00:00:51.560
to his friend, the costume
designer, William Ivey Long.

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:55.720
Rudnick began writing for
magazines including Esquire,

00:00:55.720 --> 00:00:59.620
Vogue, Vanity Fair, and Spy.

00:00:59.620 --> 00:01:03.380
Rudnick's first play
was Poor Little Lambs,

00:01:03.380 --> 00:01:06.840
a comedy about a female
Yale student's attempt

00:01:06.840 --> 00:01:12.100
to join the Whiffenpoufs, an
All-American male singing group.

00:01:12.100 --> 00:01:16.480
The play's cast included
the young then Kevin Bacon,

00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:20.400
Bronson Pinchot and Blanche Baker.

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:25.780
Rudnick then wrote two novels,
Social Disease, A Satiric Tale

00:01:25.780 --> 00:01:31.090
of New York's Nightlife in the
vein of Evelyn Waugh's Vile Bodies

00:01:31.090 --> 00:01:36.900 position:56%
and I'll Take It which was a tribute
to Rudnick's mother and aunts

00:01:36.900 --> 00:01:39.970
and their passionate
love of shopping.

00:01:39.970 --> 00:01:44.790
In the late 1980's Rudnick
moved into the top floor

00:01:44.790 --> 00:01:51.500
of a Greenwich Village brownstone
which had once been the 1920's home

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:54.930
of the actor, John Barrymore.

00:01:54.930 --> 00:02:01.560
That inspired Rudnick's play I Hate
Hamlet about a young TV star who

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:07.050
and he's about to play Hamlet is
visited by the ghost of Barrymore.

00:02:07.050 --> 00:02:14.460
In 1993, Rudnick had a breakthrough
with his off-Broadway hit Jeffrey.

00:02:14.460 --> 00:02:20.260
Rudnick has won an Obie award,
an Outer Critics Circle award

00:02:20.260 --> 00:02:24.700
and the John Gassner
Playwright award.

00:02:24.700 --> 00:02:28.050
Rudnick's later plays
included the Naked Eye,

00:02:28.050 --> 00:02:32.100
which depicted an extreme
photographer along the lines

00:02:32.100 --> 00:02:34.590
of Robert Mapplethorpe.

00:02:34.590 --> 00:02:37.920
Rudnick has worked as an
accredited script doctor

00:02:37.920 --> 00:02:43.000
on movies including the Addams
Family and The First Wives Club.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:48.250
In 2011, HarperCollins
published I Shudder,

00:02:48.250 --> 00:02:51.950
a collection of Rudnick's
autobiographical essays,

00:02:51.950 --> 00:02:56.130
some covering his work
on stage and screen.

00:02:56.130 --> 00:03:00.540
Since 1998, Rudnick has
been a frequent contributor

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:05.790
to the New Yorker, mostly of
over 50 short humor pieces.

00:03:05.790 --> 00:03:07.910
His work appears in the collections

00:03:07.910 --> 00:03:12.380
of Fierce Pajamas and
Disquiet, Please.

00:03:12.380 --> 00:03:18.210
In May 2013, scholastic
published Gorgeous,

00:03:18.210 --> 00:03:21.710
Rudnick's first adult novel.

00:03:21.710 --> 00:03:25.000
Publishers Weekly in
a starred review said

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:31.980
that the book was hilarious,
profane, and profiled.

00:03:31.980 --> 00:03:40.100
And in January 2016, his
latest book scholastic publish,

00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:47.770 position:56%
It's all Your Fault, New York Times
says, caution do not read in public,

00:03:47.770 --> 00:03:52.260
will cause you to laugh
and maybe cry out loud.

00:03:52.260 --> 00:03:58.510
Everyone please help me welcome
to the stage Mr. Paul Rudnick.

00:03:58.510 --> 00:04:07.440
[ Applause ]

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:09.520
&gt;&gt; Paul Rudnick: Oh thank you
for that wonderful introduction,

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:12.500
oops that wonderful introduction
and thank all of you so much

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:14.070
for being here and thank you.

00:04:14.070 --> 00:04:19.960
I was told that at these talks
the absolute worst sin was

00:04:19.960 --> 00:04:23.970
to read anything from cards or
notes, so I'm not going to do that.

00:04:23.970 --> 00:04:25.720
So here goes.

00:04:25.720 --> 00:04:30.490
What I wanted to talk about today
was probably the most common

00:04:30.490 --> 00:04:32.950
question that writers always get,

00:04:32.950 --> 00:04:35.990
which is where do you
get your ideas from.

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:40.170
And I had immediately thought
of so many awful answers to that

00:04:40.170 --> 00:04:43.550
like Walmart or you steal them.

00:04:43.550 --> 00:04:47.210
But what I found and I think this
happens to a lot of other writers

00:04:47.210 --> 00:04:49.630
as well is if you're
yearning to write something

00:04:49.630 --> 00:04:52.840
and the rent is due you'll often
try to do something like sit

00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:55.710
down with your notebook open
and make lists and try to figure

00:04:55.710 --> 00:04:58.900
out okay, what's a great
idea, what should I do next.

00:04:58.900 --> 00:05:05.130 position:56%
Usually those ideas vanish instantly
even if they feel sort of wonderful

00:05:05.130 --> 00:05:09.270
and inspired at the moment, they
somehow just don't take hold.

00:05:09.270 --> 00:05:11.910
What I find is there has
to be something in my life

00:05:11.910 --> 00:05:15.180
and in the larger world
that becomes so overwhelming

00:05:15.180 --> 00:05:17.450
that it insists on
being written about.

00:05:17.450 --> 00:05:21.440 position:56%
It can be personal or it can be
larger than that, but it's something

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:24.960
where you find yourself helplessly
drawn to it and you just have

00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:27.590
to start writing whether
you like it or not.

00:05:27.590 --> 00:05:31.890
So I wanted to share kind
of three brief moments

00:05:31.890 --> 00:05:34.310
of that sort of inspiration.

00:05:34.310 --> 00:05:35.610
The first actually
which was mentioned

00:05:35.610 --> 00:05:39.290
in the introduction was years ago
when I first moved to New York

00:05:39.290 --> 00:05:41.560
and this will show you
how long ago this was

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:43.860
because it involves real estate.

00:05:43.860 --> 00:05:47.710
This was when if you wanted an
apartment you could actually look

00:05:47.710 --> 00:05:52.260 position:56%
at the real estate listings in the
New York Times or the Village Voice,

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:56.880
wander over to a building,
take a look, wait a day

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:00.040
or so before deciding
to pay the very low rent

00:06:00.040 --> 00:06:01.620
and there you have an apartment.

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:05.700
This has been unheard of for
about the past 30 years now.

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:09.670
But when I first arrived, I saw a
listing I think it was in the Times

00:06:09.670 --> 00:06:14.870
that intrigued me because
it said medieval duplex.

00:06:14.870 --> 00:06:18.250
And I thought okay, what's
medieval about it, you know,

00:06:18.250 --> 00:06:20.580
is it the plumbing,
is it the landlord.

00:06:20.580 --> 00:06:22.920
So immediately I went
and it was the top floor

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:25.460
of a brownstone right
off Washington Square.

00:06:25.460 --> 00:06:27.720
So it was the romantic ideal

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:30.090
of every young artist
moving to New York.

00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:32.990
It was a garret basically,
but a very nice one

00:06:32.990 --> 00:06:39.460
with the full top floor and it had
been the nest of John Barrymore,

00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:44.320
the famous actor who lived there
actually beginning at around 1901,

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:46.910
when he was playing
Hamlet on Broadway.

00:06:46.910 --> 00:06:49.500
And he remodeled the
whole place as something

00:06:49.500 --> 00:06:52.410
which he called the
alchemist's corner.

00:06:52.410 --> 00:06:55.340
So it really had the most
marvelous enchanted feeling.

00:06:55.340 --> 00:06:58.940
There were stained-glass windows
and an enormous skylight and up

00:06:58.940 --> 00:07:01.530
on the roof there was
a tiny cottage.

00:07:01.530 --> 00:07:03.020
Which from my research I found

00:07:03.020 --> 00:07:07.380 position:56%
out Barrymore had planted the entire
roof and added a reflecting pool,

00:07:07.380 --> 00:07:10.270
all of which was not up to
code, so it eventually collapsed

00:07:10.270 --> 00:07:11.570
into the apartment below.

00:07:11.570 --> 00:07:14.610
But that had been repaired
by the time I got there.

00:07:14.610 --> 00:07:17.770
So I looked around with
a real estate agent

00:07:17.770 --> 00:07:23.740
and I was immediately drawn to
it, but I wasn't quite sure.

00:07:23.740 --> 00:07:26.960
So that I went home and I
called my very first agent,

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:30.300
this wonderful woman named Helen
Merrill, who even then was already

00:07:30.300 --> 00:07:32.400
in her 70's and very German.

00:07:32.400 --> 00:07:36.110
She moved to Germany
before the war as a refugee,

00:07:36.110 --> 00:07:38.320
but still had the thickest accent.

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:40.830
And I said Helen, I'm
looking at this apartment

00:07:40.830 --> 00:07:44.250
with this Barrymore
pedigree and she said,

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:50.370
oh Rudnick perhaps you
have found my hairpins.

00:07:50.370 --> 00:07:53.630
Because it turned out that
Helen had had an affair

00:07:53.630 --> 00:07:57.700
with Barrymore's son-in-law
on the premises.

00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:01.420
So at that point it sort of
became impossible not to write

00:08:01.420 --> 00:08:04.340
about the apartment
once I had moved in.

00:08:04.340 --> 00:08:09.020
And I began writing a novel
that was called I Hate Hamlet

00:08:09.020 --> 00:08:10.770
because somehow it felt

00:08:10.770 --> 00:08:13.450
like a literary Greenwich
Village thing to do.

00:08:13.450 --> 00:08:16.430
But eventually because it was
about actors and it was all set

00:08:16.430 --> 00:08:21.770
in a single room it became a
play, I just let it happen.

00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:25.490
And it eventually ended
up on Broadway in a sort

00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:28.320
of wildly adventurous
and traumatic run

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:32.830
because what happened
was we cast this insane,

00:08:32.830 --> 00:08:38.840 position:56%
oops oh this insane wildly alcoholic
English actor named Nicol Williamson

00:08:38.840 --> 00:08:41.320
was playing the ghost
of John Barrymore.

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:44.570
And he was the kind of guy who
the first time I met him was

00:08:44.570 --> 00:08:48.960
at a restaurant where the table was
filled with two empty wine bottles,

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:54.140
a can of beer, a few cocktails
and because he was so known

00:08:54.140 --> 00:08:57.080
as a drunkard when someone asked,

00:08:57.080 --> 00:09:00.210
are you still drinking he
said no, not in months.

00:09:00.210 --> 00:09:03.450
And there was that moment
where you thought do we point

00:09:03.450 --> 00:09:07.520
to the glassware, you know, and I
just thought I hope for the best.

00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:10.170
And Nicol on his good
nights could be inspired

00:09:10.170 --> 00:09:11.680
and the play just soared.

00:09:11.680 --> 00:09:16.260 position:56%
And on his lesser nights the first
act ended with a big climactic dual,

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:19.180
a sword fight that took
place all over the stage.

00:09:19.180 --> 00:09:22.540
And Nicol's costar was the very
young actor named Evan Handler,

00:09:22.540 --> 00:09:24.780
who you may know from Sex
in the City and all sorts

00:09:24.780 --> 00:09:29.370
of television things and Evan was
wonderful, wonderful, very talented

00:09:29.370 --> 00:09:31.460
and wonderfully patient as well.

00:09:31.460 --> 00:09:35.720
But Nicol did not want any costar,

00:09:35.720 --> 00:09:38.140
let alone one who was
much younger than he was.

00:09:38.140 --> 00:09:41.450
Nicol had called me one
morning at 3 a.m. to tell me

00:09:41.450 --> 00:09:44.860
that he felt he could
play both leading roles.

00:09:44.860 --> 00:09:46.770
It's one of those questions

00:09:46.770 --> 00:09:50.230
where you don't know do I
ask how you would do that,

00:09:50.230 --> 00:09:52.660
how you would have a
sword fight with yourself.

00:09:52.660 --> 00:09:56.550
But Nicol took it into his head
and then one night during the run,

00:09:56.550 --> 00:09:59.780
during the sword fight he
took after Evan for real

00:09:59.780 --> 00:10:03.150
and stabbed him and drew blood.

00:10:03.150 --> 00:10:06.670
And I was not there that evening,
but the next day I came downstairs

00:10:06.670 --> 00:10:12.530
and the full front page of the
New York Post said, I hit Hamlet,

00:10:12.530 --> 00:10:16.150
star stabs actor in the butt,

00:10:16.150 --> 00:10:20.550
which if you know the paper it's
sort of New York Post poetry.

00:10:20.550 --> 00:10:24.660
So with that kind of experience
from that moment of walking

00:10:24.660 --> 00:10:27.150
into an apartment I never
knew where this was headed,

00:10:27.150 --> 00:10:29.820
but I knew I had to write about it.

00:10:29.820 --> 00:10:35.100
So that was my first moment of okay
inspiration appears from anywhere.

00:10:35.100 --> 00:10:40.130
The next thing I'd like to
get into was more serious

00:10:40.130 --> 00:10:43.760
and affected far more people,
which was by that point we were

00:10:43.760 --> 00:10:48.910
into late 80's, early 90's and I
was a gay man living in New York.

00:10:48.910 --> 00:10:52.440
And so many people, an overwhelming
amount of people I knew were sick

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:56.400
or dying of AIDS and it
was a terrifying time.

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:58.040
This was before there
were any treatments.

00:10:58.040 --> 00:11:01.620
This was while the government was
completely ignoring the illness.

00:11:01.620 --> 00:11:05.210
This was where even medical
personnel were unwilling sometimes

00:11:05.210 --> 00:11:08.270
to treat or touch people
who were infected.

00:11:08.270 --> 00:11:12.760
And because I'm a comic writer
at that time I couldn't imagine

00:11:12.760 --> 00:11:17.190
that I had any place in
writing about the plague years

00:11:17.190 --> 00:11:18.600
and about the people I knew,

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:22.370
it just felt like the
most awful contradiction.

00:11:22.370 --> 00:11:25.590
But then one day, actually it was
also mentioned in my introduction,

00:11:25.590 --> 00:11:27.350
a dear friend of mine,
William Ivey Long,

00:11:27.350 --> 00:11:28.970
who is a true Southern gentleman

00:11:28.970 --> 00:11:32.310
and a brilliant Tony
award-winning costume designer.

00:11:32.310 --> 00:11:35.290
He and I were going to the hospital
to visit another good friend

00:11:35.290 --> 00:11:38.770
of ours named Eric who was
very, very ill and would die.

00:11:38.770 --> 00:11:43.360
And Eric was emaciated,
was hallucinating,

00:11:43.360 --> 00:11:46.250
and also his room was quarantined.

00:11:46.250 --> 00:11:51.100
It was still the most --
everything about it only got worse.

00:11:51.100 --> 00:11:55.380
But Eric what was so strange
is Eric had many friends,

00:11:55.380 --> 00:11:57.550
so he must have been
visited quite a bit.

00:11:57.550 --> 00:12:00.990
But he was refusing to
kind of live up to his role

00:12:00.990 --> 00:12:04.810
as a noble sick person
and why should he.

00:12:04.810 --> 00:12:08.930
But Eric was doing things like
demanding exactly the right shade

00:12:08.930 --> 00:12:12.820
of towels in the right
amount of Egyptian cotton.

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:16.120
And if you brought him a
beverage it had to be, you know,

00:12:16.120 --> 00:12:18.740
grape-ade not lime-ade,
not lemonade.

00:12:18.740 --> 00:12:21.850
If you brought him the fashion
magazines that he loved they had

00:12:21.850 --> 00:12:25.950 position:56%
to be French Vogue and Italian Vogue
because American Vogue was trashy.

00:12:25.950 --> 00:12:28.720
So he became so insistent
on everything

00:12:28.720 --> 00:12:31.090
and nothing was ever good enough
and of course, because he was

00:12:31.090 --> 00:12:34.770
in such a terrible state we wanted
to please him and do anything

00:12:34.770 --> 00:12:36.210
to ease what he was going through.

00:12:36.210 --> 00:12:40.570 position:56%
But that morning, that visit William
and I went out to a park bench

00:12:40.570 --> 00:12:42.820
in front of the hospital
afterwards after a couple

00:12:42.820 --> 00:12:44.750
of hours of being be harangued.

00:12:44.750 --> 00:12:46.780
And William turned
to me and he said,

00:12:46.780 --> 00:12:51.800
you know I love Eric very dearly
and I will do anything for him,

00:12:51.800 --> 00:12:55.440
but my God I want to slap him.

00:12:55.440 --> 00:12:58.820
And we both looked at each other
and the whole situation was

00:12:58.820 --> 00:13:00.760
so unbearably awful and tragic

00:13:00.760 --> 00:13:03.030
that all we could do
was burst out laughing.

00:13:03.030 --> 00:13:06.600
And I realized that so many of
the people I knew were getting

00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:10.290
through all of this with the
only weapon in their possession,

00:13:10.290 --> 00:13:11.750
which was a sense of humor.

00:13:11.750 --> 00:13:13.830
That people were marching
and people were helping

00:13:13.830 --> 00:13:17.230
and people were joining Act Up
and every possible organization,

00:13:17.230 --> 00:13:20.370
but these were some of
the most stylish and funny

00:13:20.370 --> 00:13:22.090
and extraordinary people
I've ever met.

00:13:22.090 --> 00:13:26.890
Men and women, gay and straight,
it just was something to behold.

00:13:26.890 --> 00:13:29.500
And I thought oh okay that's
what I want to write about.

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:33.890
And that moment and all of the
stuff that seems impossible and all

00:13:33.890 --> 00:13:38.970
of the stuff that somehow becomes
hilarious in the face of death.

00:13:38.970 --> 00:13:41.520
So I wrote this play
called Jeffrey and it was

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:42.820
about a guy -- it was funny again.

00:13:42.820 --> 00:13:45.890
Again, it was a character that
began in another play I was working

00:13:45.890 --> 00:13:49.260
on about another sort
of story entirely.

00:13:49.260 --> 00:13:52.380
But there was this one guy who
was giving up sex who said well

00:13:52.380 --> 00:13:56.160
that was the only possible way to
deal with the AIDS crisis was kind

00:13:56.160 --> 00:13:58.820
of to run from it and to
run from romance and to run

00:13:58.820 --> 00:14:00.870
from any kind of personal contact.

00:14:00.870 --> 00:14:02.720
And that seemed like
a strong storyline,

00:14:02.720 --> 00:14:04.780
so that became the center.

00:14:04.780 --> 00:14:09.160
And once I'd written the play
Helen my agent again submitted

00:14:09.160 --> 00:14:12.340
to every theater in New York,
all of whom turned it down.

00:14:12.340 --> 00:14:14.820
Even the people who liked it
would write me letters saying,

00:14:14.820 --> 00:14:18.260
oh well I enjoyed this, our
audience would never stand for it.

00:14:18.260 --> 00:14:23.310 position:56%
It just became known - they said how
can you have a comedy about AIDS.

00:14:23.310 --> 00:14:25.450
And Helen finally went
to a tiny theater

00:14:25.450 --> 00:14:27.200
on 23rd Street called the WPA

00:14:27.200 --> 00:14:30.760
and she sat outside the
artistic director's office

00:14:30.760 --> 00:14:33.030
and would not leave
till he read the play.

00:14:33.030 --> 00:14:35.620
And then wouldn't leave
until he agreed to do it.

00:14:35.620 --> 00:14:38.590
So the man named Kyle
Renick who was wonderful

00:14:38.590 --> 00:14:40.070
and I was just so grateful.

00:14:40.070 --> 00:14:42.670
So it was set for like
a three-week run.

00:14:42.670 --> 00:14:45.430
Every actor New York was
warned away from this play.

00:14:45.430 --> 00:14:47.310
They were told it would
ruin their careers.

00:14:47.310 --> 00:14:49.260
They were told it was far too gay.

00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:53.080
And it was -- the worst thing
you can do to actors is try

00:14:53.080 --> 00:14:57.300
to scare them about
completely ridiculous concerns.

00:14:57.300 --> 00:15:00.620
So the people we ended up with I
just was so deeply grateful for.

